ground_truth:
The greatest common factor of $145b^2$ and $29b$ is $29b$. We factor $29b$ out of both terms to get:\begin{align*}
145b^2 +29b &= 29b \cdot 5b+ 29b \cdot 1\\
&=\boxed{29b(5b+1)}.
\end{align*}

Multiplying the numerator and denominator by the conjugate of the denominator, we have \begin{align*}
\dfrac{3+4i}{1+2i} \cdot \frac{1-2i}{1-2i} &= \frac{3(1) + 3(-2i) + 4i(1) + 4i(-2i)}{1(1) + 1(-2i) + 2i(1) -2i(2i)} \\
&= \dfrac{11-2i}{5} = \boxed{\dfrac{11}{5} - \dfrac{2}{5}i}.
\end{align*}

We can find this answer by plugging 5 into the function: \begin{align*} f(5)& = \dfrac{5+1}{3(5)-4}
\\ & = \dfrac{6}{15-4}
\\ & = \boxed{\dfrac{6}{11}}
\end{align*}

The line $x = k$ intersects the graph of the parabola $x = -2y^2 - 3y + 5$ at exactly one point if and only if the equation $-2y^2 - 3y + 5 = k$ has exactly one real solution.  This equation is equivalent to \[2y^2 + 3y + (k - 5) = 0,\] and this equation has exactly one real solution if and only if the discriminant is 0.  The discriminant of this quadratic is $3^2 - 4 \cdot 2 \cdot (k - 5)$.  Setting this equal to 0 and solving for $k$, we find $k = \boxed{\frac{49}{8}}$.  (Note that this is the $x$-coordinate of the vertex of the parabola.)

